00:03:43.900 --> 00:03:48.250
Just as background,
William Rosen

00:03:48.250 --> 00:03:50.680
wrote this book called
The Industrial Revolution

00:03:50.680 --> 00:03:55.600
in Britain, and he has
important lessons for us

00:03:55.600 --> 00:03:58.830
on the process of innovation,
and I'll just recap.

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:02.890
I'll just pull out of that book
some thoughts that may help us

00:04:02.890 --> 00:04:06.850
think a little bit in the
big picture kind of way

00:04:06.850 --> 00:04:09.170
about some of these issues.

00:04:09.170 --> 00:04:13.500
First, he identifies something
called the intelligent hand.

00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:18.420
And that concept is
taken from Charles Bell,

00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:21.300
but it really originates
in Immanuel Kant

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:24.750
who identified the hand
as a window in the world.

00:04:24.750 --> 00:04:29.850
And since MIT's model is mind
and hand, in other words,

00:04:29.850 --> 00:04:32.780
in many ways, it's
learning by doing,

00:04:32.780 --> 00:04:35.360
that's an important
conceptual framework

00:04:35.360 --> 00:04:38.690
when we begin to think about
innovation that's clearly not

00:04:38.690 --> 00:04:39.710
mind only.

00:04:39.710 --> 00:04:41.480
It is clearly mind and hand.

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:43.010
It's the combination
of the ability

00:04:43.010 --> 00:04:45.290
to do things physically
and in a tactile way,

00:04:45.290 --> 00:04:48.477
carry them out as well as
think those great conceptual

00:04:48.477 --> 00:04:49.310
organizing thoughts.

00:04:52.890 --> 00:04:58.350
Davinci combines,
and I've just been

00:04:58.350 --> 00:05:00.360
reading a biography
of him, but he

00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:04.050
amazingly in his thousands
of pages of notebooks

00:05:04.050 --> 00:05:09.760
combines his incredible
ability to do art and draw

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:14.920
with his highly inventive
skill set of imagining

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:17.110
all kinds of new
machines, right,

00:05:17.110 --> 00:05:19.810
that were unimagined in
the context of the 1500's

00:05:19.810 --> 00:05:22.010
when he's writing.

00:05:22.010 --> 00:05:23.285
Helicopters, as one example.

00:05:26.820 --> 00:05:32.250
His ability to see and
conceptually see and draw

00:05:32.250 --> 00:05:36.720
helps enable him to invent
these big conceptual ideas.

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:40.550
So that's another way of
looking at mind and hand.

00:05:40.550 --> 00:05:41.160
Right.

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:43.710
Another way of looking
at the intelligent hand.

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:47.280
So Rosen argues that the
visual, and the tactile,

00:05:47.280 --> 00:05:51.000
and the mind, and the
eye, and the hand,

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:58.320
are all critical in this
innovation invention process.

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:04.500
Just to quote-- to take a few
moments here and pull moments

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:06.510
out of his book,
one is what he calls

00:06:06.510 --> 00:06:07.830
the flash of insight problem.

00:06:07.830 --> 00:06:12.060
And the example he
provides is James Watt

00:06:12.060 --> 00:06:15.080
is walking on the
green of Glasgow.

00:06:15.080 --> 00:06:18.980
And in that moment,
and, of course,

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:23.620
it's Scotland, so he's
walking past the golf shack.

00:06:23.620 --> 00:06:24.120
Right.

00:06:24.120 --> 00:06:24.870
Where else?

00:06:24.870 --> 00:06:25.820
Right.

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:30.200
He has the idea for
condensation in achieving

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:33.150
a much higher level of
efficiency of steam power.

00:06:33.150 --> 00:06:37.580
So, there are steam engines
working in mines prior to Watt,

00:06:37.580 --> 00:06:43.850
but it's that walk on
the green where he writes

00:06:43.850 --> 00:06:46.980
that the inside came together.

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:50.740
But, we have to put
this into the context.

00:06:50.740 --> 00:06:53.890
His insight, as he's walking
next to the golf shack,

00:06:53.890 --> 00:06:57.130
appears effortless,
but it's built

00:06:57.130 --> 00:07:02.710
on a long term project
of understanding

00:07:02.710 --> 00:07:04.660
how steam power worked.

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:07.420
And Watt is an
interesting figure

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:11.320
because he comes out of a
poor background in Scotland.

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:13.990
He gets-- he's a
skilled artisan.

00:07:13.990 --> 00:07:17.420
He becomes an instrument maker.

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:20.330
So, he's working on early
scientific, and navigational,

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:24.290
and astronomy instruments.

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:27.170
And he works in London,
and he's exposed

00:07:27.170 --> 00:07:30.110
to the finest skilled
artisans working

00:07:30.110 --> 00:07:31.910
on those early
scientific instruments.

00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:34.670
He comes back to Glasgow.

00:07:34.670 --> 00:07:38.450
He's blocked by the local
Guild from setting up

00:07:38.450 --> 00:07:41.533
his own instrument shop.

00:07:41.533 --> 00:07:42.450
What's he going to do?

00:07:42.450 --> 00:07:45.290
He takes a job at the
University of Edinburgh

00:07:45.290 --> 00:07:47.430
and actually becomes
quite a close friend

00:07:47.430 --> 00:07:51.980
of Adam Smith who's inventing
economics at the same time.

00:07:51.980 --> 00:07:57.730
And he digs into, in
depth, into steam engines,

00:07:57.730 --> 00:08:01.300
and begins to develop
concepts of how they actually

00:08:01.300 --> 00:08:02.260
function and work.

00:08:02.260 --> 00:08:05.050
I mean, this is
pre-thermodynamics.

00:08:05.050 --> 00:08:10.680
But Watt is developing a
lot of those early idea

00:08:10.680 --> 00:08:17.080
concepts that will lead to that
conceptual kind of framework.

00:08:17.080 --> 00:08:18.710
And he spends 10
years on that project

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:20.740
before he has the
walk on the green.

00:08:20.740 --> 00:08:21.380
Right.

00:08:21.380 --> 00:08:23.100
Doing these various projects.

00:08:23.100 --> 00:08:28.850
So it's that 10 years
that enables the insight.

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:32.900
So, Anders Ericsson who
Rosen also writes about

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:35.700
develops the expert
performance model.

00:08:35.700 --> 00:08:37.700
Its time on task.

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:40.049
It's not talent alone.

00:08:40.049 --> 00:08:43.049
So, it's really important
to do those 10,000

00:08:43.049 --> 00:08:46.350
hours of practicing
before you can pretend

00:08:46.350 --> 00:08:48.550
to be a serious musician.

00:08:48.550 --> 00:08:49.790
Right.

00:08:49.790 --> 00:08:53.250
So, you may appear
musically fluent,

00:08:53.250 --> 00:08:55.910
but those 10,000
hours of practice

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:58.990
turn out to be absolutely
critical foundations.

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:03.210
So, it's this combination
of expert performance,

00:09:03.210 --> 00:09:06.670
Anders Ericsson
Ericsson would argue,

00:09:06.670 --> 00:09:08.920
with that intellectual
capability

00:09:08.920 --> 00:09:11.050
that's very key here.

00:09:11.050 --> 00:09:14.710
Michael Polanyi, a
philosopher and psychologist

00:09:14.710 --> 00:09:17.290
thinks about learning by doing.

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:19.700
What does that
process look like?

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:24.250
And he develops a whole
concept of tactile knowing,

00:09:24.250 --> 00:09:28.270
that it's a combination
of knowledge and skills,

00:09:28.270 --> 00:09:31.360
actual physical tactile
kinds of skills.

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:36.880
Eric Kandel begins the work
in neuroscience and beginning

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:42.420
to tell us how
learning can occur.

00:09:42.420 --> 00:09:53.050
And he's there great Columbia
neuroscientist Nobel winner.

00:09:53.050 --> 00:09:59.460
He tells us how
the brain chemistry

00:09:59.460 --> 00:10:05.040
changes in the course of
actual tactile experience.

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:06.900
Right.

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:10.250
Which helps us
understand why that--

00:10:10.250 --> 00:10:14.900
its mind and hand
in combination.

00:10:14.900 --> 00:10:18.300
So, let me let me
leave those there.

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:20.840
And then, turn to Warren
Bennis and Patricia Ward

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:24.950
Biederman who wrote this book
called Organizing Genius back

00:10:24.950 --> 00:10:28.070
in 1997.

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:32.920
So Bennis had been an
MIT faculty member.

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:35.470
He became president of
a university in Ohio.

00:10:35.470 --> 00:10:37.840
He then moved to
teach business at USC,

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:42.630
which is where he's writing this
book from along with Patricia

00:10:42.630 --> 00:10:44.340
Biderman from USC.

00:10:46.940 --> 00:10:50.420
And they, after watching closely
a lot of innovation groups,

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:54.570
as you all saw, they
develop the idea

00:10:54.570 --> 00:11:00.390
that these groups seem to
operate on rule systems.

00:11:00.390 --> 00:11:03.810
That there are kind of
rules to govern a group.

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:06.540
And that these different
innovation groups

00:11:06.540 --> 00:11:09.870
share a lot of rules.

00:11:09.870 --> 00:11:12.320
So, that's the key
concept here that we're

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:14.930
going to be playing when we
discuss our great groups here

00:11:14.930 --> 00:11:15.490
in class.

00:11:20.010 --> 00:11:22.215
And they run through--

00:11:22.215 --> 00:11:24.090
I'll just run through
some of the basic rules

00:11:24.090 --> 00:11:26.160
that you all, you know,
by now are familiar with,

00:11:26.160 --> 00:11:30.260
but they argue that greatness
starts with superb people.

00:11:30.260 --> 00:11:33.520
And they quote Bob
Taylor of Xerox PARC,

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:35.270
you can't pile together
enough good people

00:11:35.270 --> 00:11:37.550
to make a great one.

00:11:37.550 --> 00:11:42.490
That great groups and great
leaders both need each other,

00:11:42.490 --> 00:11:44.650
and create each other,
and enable each other,

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:48.080
that it's not leadership
alone, it's the group

00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:50.530
and the group needs leadership.

00:11:50.530 --> 00:11:52.630
But the leadership have
got to be able to play off

00:11:52.630 --> 00:11:54.670
of and interact with a group.

00:11:54.670 --> 00:11:58.410
And we'll see different
leadership styles

00:11:58.410 --> 00:12:00.130
in putting these
great groups together

00:12:00.130 --> 00:12:02.860
as we talk about
these groups today.

00:12:02.860 --> 00:12:06.230
Great group leaders love
talent and know how to find it.

00:12:06.230 --> 00:12:06.730
Right.

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:08.290
That's to create
a great group you

00:12:08.290 --> 00:12:10.060
got have great talent in it.

00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:14.690
And a role of the great group
leader is to find that talent.

00:12:14.690 --> 00:12:18.670
The talent in great
groups can work together.

00:12:18.670 --> 00:12:20.980
And in the Oppenheimer
story, Beth,

00:12:20.980 --> 00:12:24.220
you're going to tell us some
of the dissonance points

00:12:24.220 --> 00:12:28.060
I'm sure in that great group.

00:12:28.060 --> 00:12:30.580
And certainly-- and Martin
and the Bardeen, Brattain,

00:12:30.580 --> 00:12:32.440
and Shockley story,
you're going to tell us

00:12:32.440 --> 00:12:35.020
about some of the dissidents
in that great group

00:12:35.020 --> 00:12:37.530
that kind of blew it up.

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:40.010
Great groups like to think
they're on a mission from God.

00:12:40.010 --> 00:12:41.547
In other words,
they have to believe

00:12:41.547 --> 00:12:43.380
that this is the most
important mission that

00:12:43.380 --> 00:12:44.505
could ever possibly happen.

00:12:44.505 --> 00:12:46.450
Otherwise, they
never get anywhere.

00:12:46.450 --> 00:12:48.800
So they have enormous zeal.

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:49.440
Right.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:51.450
And it's almost a
kind of religious zeal

00:12:51.450 --> 00:12:55.590
as they embark on
their projects.

00:12:55.590 --> 00:12:57.810
They wear blinders.

00:12:57.810 --> 00:13:01.470
In other words, they can
focus only on their project.

00:13:01.470 --> 00:13:07.960
They can stay on task And
make that their entire focus.

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:10.450
Otherwise, again,
would they get there?

00:13:10.450 --> 00:13:11.770
They are optimistic.

00:13:11.770 --> 00:13:13.960
They are not realistic.

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:17.470
So, if they were realistic
about what they were attempting,

00:13:17.470 --> 00:13:19.790
they would never try it.

00:13:19.790 --> 00:13:22.700
But, because they
are optimists, they

00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:25.670
have the willingness to
persevere in the expectation

00:13:25.670 --> 00:13:28.120
that something is
going to happen.

00:13:28.120 --> 00:13:30.310
Great groups are islands,
but they have a bridge

00:13:30.310 --> 00:13:31.180
to the mainland.

00:13:31.180 --> 00:13:34.250
So, Luyao, when she tells us
about the Xerox PARC story,

00:13:34.250 --> 00:13:37.240
is going to tell us the
classic island bridge story.

00:13:37.240 --> 00:13:41.100
But typically, great
groups need to get put

00:13:41.100 --> 00:13:44.040
on an island, a
protected island,

00:13:44.040 --> 00:13:45.870
out of the control
of bureaucracies,

00:13:45.870 --> 00:13:49.260
out of the control
of the suits, where

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:50.880
they can do their
own thing, where

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:53.040
they can come up
with their inventions

00:13:53.040 --> 00:13:55.650
and then innovations.

00:13:55.650 --> 00:13:58.110
But, nothing happens
to those innovations

00:13:58.110 --> 00:14:01.490
unless they have a bridge
back to decision makers

00:14:01.490 --> 00:14:04.350
that enable those technologies
to get effectuated,

00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:06.210
to be put into place.

00:14:06.210 --> 00:14:08.370
Great groups have an enemy.

00:14:08.370 --> 00:14:11.880
Probably the most
famous in your time,

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:13.380
maybe you're all
too young for this,

00:14:13.380 --> 00:14:16.590
remember those big blue
commercials that Steve Jobs ran

00:14:16.590 --> 00:14:19.530
during super bowls?

00:14:19.530 --> 00:14:27.930
You know attacking IBM and its
minions who were wearing suits

00:14:27.930 --> 00:14:31.470
in this kind of dark
Orwellian advertisement

00:14:31.470 --> 00:14:34.000
talking about Apple
is up against this,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.230
you know, authoritarian
IBM enemy.

00:14:37.230 --> 00:14:37.950
Right.

00:14:37.950 --> 00:14:41.020
It was a shocking
ad at the time.

00:14:41.020 --> 00:14:43.020
But it gives you a
very good example

00:14:43.020 --> 00:14:46.050
of just how it felt to
be at Apple pushing up

00:14:46.050 --> 00:14:51.750
against IBM's PC trying to
get your Mac out the door.

